description:
Why: Clients need to detect which messages entered/left a query result set since a last-known state (e.g. for incremental chat message list sync). This is the standard RFC 8620 §5.6 /queryChanges endpoint applied to messages.

What: Add message_query_changes() to message.rs, returning QueryChangesResponse.

Algorithm:
1. Open crates/jmap-chat/src/methods/message.rs
2. Add QueryChangesResponse to the use super::{ ... } import
3. Add this method to the impl JmapChatClient block:

/// Fetch query-result changes for Message since 
/// (RFC 8620 §5.6 / Message/queryChanges).
///
/// Returns which message IDs were removed from or added to the query
/// result set since the given state.  may be None.
pub async fn message_query_changes(
    &self,
    session: &crate::jmap::Session,
    since_query_state: &str,
    max_changes: Option<u64>,
) -> Result<QueryChangesResponse, crate::error::ClientError> {
    let (api_url, account_id) = Self::session_parts(session)?;
    let mut args = serde_json::json!({
        "accountId": account_id,
        "sinceQueryState": since_query_state,
    });
    if let Some(mc) = max_changes {
        args["maxChanges"] = mc.into();
    }
    let (call_id, req) = super::build_request("Message/queryChanges", args);
    let resp = self.call(api_url, &req).await?;
    crate::client::extract_response(resp, call_id)
}

4. Run cargo check to verify compilation.

Pattern: This exactly matches custom_emoji_query_changes (in custom_emoji.rs), which is the established pattern for queryChanges in this codebase. max_changes follows omit-when-None pattern (not null) per RFC 8620 §5.6 which says max_changes is UnsignedInt (not nullable in queryChanges, unlike /changes).

Wait — actually RFC 8620 §5.6 says maxChanges is UnsignedInt (non-nullable for /queryChanges). So omit when None is correct here.
